## STRIDE Threat Model – Multi‑Region Amazon EKS Deployment  

Below is a **structured STRIDE analysis** of the architecture sketched in the Python diagram script.  
For each STRIDE category we list:

| Threat | Where it can manifest in the diagram | Likely impact | Recommended remediation (secure‑by‑design) |
|--------|--------------------------------------|---------------|--------------------------------------------|

| **S – Spoofing** | • API Gateway endpoints that are publicly reachable.<br>• IAM roles attached to EKS worker nodes and service accounts.<br>• Users/clients that authenticate through the “Users” on‑prem node. | An attacker may impersonate a legitimate client, obtain a valid JWT/OIDC token, or assume an IAM role with more privileges than intended. | 1. **Enforce strong, short‑lived OIDC tokens** (e.g., Amazon Cognito or an external IdP) and enable **token introspection** at the API Gateway.<br>2. **Enable IAM OpenID Connect (OIDC) provider** for the cluster and bind **Kubernetes Service Accounts → IAM Roles** with the **least‑privilege** policy (see “IAM least‑privilege example” below).<br>3. **Mutual TLS (mTLS)** between API Gateway and the internal NLB/ALB that fronts the EKS services. |
| **T – Tampering** | • Public API payloads that reach the EKS services.<br>• Configurations stored in EFS (shared file system) and DynamoDB (state).<br>• Kubernetes manifests applied via `kubectl` or CI/CD pipelines. | Modification of request/response data, injection of malicious containers, or alteration of persisted data. | 1. **Enable AWS WAF** on the API Gateway with rules that block SQLi, XSS, and known bad payloads.<br>2. **Sign and verify all container images** using **Amazon ECR image signing (Docker Content Trust)** and enforce **Admission Controllers** (e.g., OPA Gatekeeper) that reject unsigned images.<br>3. **Encrypt EFS at rest** (AWS‑managed KMS) and **enable in‑flight TLS** for all EFS mounts (EFS‑TLS).<br>4. **Enable DynamoDB encryption at rest** and **point‑in‑time recovery (PITR)** to detect and roll‑back tampering. |
| **R – Repudiation** | • API Gateway logs and CloudTrail events are not explicitly shown.<br>• EKS audit logs may be missing or not forwarded. | An attacker could perform actions and later deny having done so, making forensic analysis difficult. | 1. **Enable AWS CloudTrail data‑event logging** for API Gateway, EKS, and DynamoDB. Forward logs to **Amazon CloudWatch Logs** and **Amazon S3** with immutable bucket policies (Object Lock).<br>2. **Enable EKS audit logging** (Kubernetes API server audit) and ship logs to **Amazon OpenSearch Service** or a SIEM for tamper‑evident storage.<br>3. **Use AWS Config** to record configuration changes and **AWS Security Hub** for continuous compliance alerts. |
| **I – Information Disclosure** | • Public API endpoints expose data to the internet.<br>• EFS shares may be mounted by pods in multiple namespaces.<br>• DynamoDB tables may have overly permissive IAM policies. | Leakage of PII, business logic, or internal configuration to unauthenticated parties. | 1. **Restrict API Gateway to HTTPS only** and enforce **TLS 1.2+** with strong cipher suites.<br>2. **Apply fine‑grained IAM policies** on DynamoDB (see example) and enable **DynamoDB encryption at rest**.<br>3. **Use Kubernetes NetworkPolicies** to isolate namespaces and limit which pods can mount the EFS volume.<br>4. **Enable VPC‑endpoint policies** for EFS and DynamoDB to keep traffic within the VPC. |
| **D – Denial‑of‑Service** | • Public API Gateway can be flooded with requests.<br>• Unrestricted inbound rules on the VPC/ELB.<br>• EKS worker nodes may be overwhelmed by malformed traffic. | Service outage for legitimate users, increased cost, or forced scaling beyond budget. | 1. **Configure AWS WAF rate‑based rules** (e.g., 1000 requests/5 min per IP) on the API Gateway.<br>2. **Enable ELB/ALB request throttling** and **target group health checks** to automatically deregister unhealthy pods.<br>3. **Set up Cluster Autoscaler** with **max‑node‑count limits** and **budget alerts** (AWS Budgets).<br>4. **Deploy a Kubernetes PodDisruptionBudget (PDB)** for critical services to avoid cascading failures. |
| **E – Elevation of Privilege** | • IAM role attached to the EKS node group may have broad permissions (e.g., `*:*`).<br>• Service accounts in pods may inherit node IAM role (IRSA not used).<br>• Lack of Pod Security Policies (PSP) or OPA policies. | An attacker who compromises a container can gain broader AWS permissions, read/write other resources, or pivot to the control plane. | 1. **Adopt IAM Roles for Service Accounts (IRSA)** – each pod gets a dedicated IAM role with the minimum actions it needs.<br>2. **Disable the default node‑instance role for pod access** (set `--disable-legacy-iam` in the EKS control plane).<br>3. **Enforce Pod Security Standards** (restricted) via **OPA Gatekeeper** or **Kubernetes PodSecurityAdmission**.<br>4. **Use AWS Secrets Manager** (or Parameter Store) for credentials; never embed secrets in container images or ConfigMaps. |

---

## Secure‑by‑Design Remediation Checklist  

| Area | Action | Reference (AWS docs) |
|------|--------|----------------------|
| **Identity & Access Management** | • Create **least‑privilege IAM policies** for EKS node role, service‑account roles, DynamoDB, and EFS.<br>• Enable **IAM Access Analyzer** to detect over‑privileged policies. | <https://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/UserGuide/access_policies.html> |
| **Network Segmentation** | • Deploy each region’s VPC with **private subnets** for EKS workers; expose only the API Gateway via **public subnets**.<br>• Apply **Security Group** rules that allow inbound traffic only from the API Gateway CIDR. | <https://docs.aws.amazon.com/eks/latest/userguide/network-requirements.html> |
| **API Protection** | • Attach **AWS WAF** to the API Gateway with OWASP Core Rule Set.<br>• Enable **API throttling** and **usage plans**. | <https://docs.aws.amazon.com/apigateway/latest/developerguide/waf.html> |
| **Container Image Integrity** | • Store images in **Amazon ECR** with **image scanning** and **image signing** (ECR Notary).<br>• Enforce **Admission Controller** that rejects unsigned images. | <https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECR/latest/userguide/image-scanning.html> |
| **Logging & Monitoring** | • CloudTrail **Data Events** for S3, DynamoDB, EKS, and API Gateway.<br>• Forward **EKS audit logs** to CloudWatch Logs and enable **log retention** with immutable S3 bucket.<br>• Enable **GuardDuty**, **Security Hub**, and **Amazon Detective** for threat detection. | <https://docs.aws.amazon.com/eks/latest/userguide/control-plane-logging.html> |
| **Data Protection** | • Enable **EFS encryption at rest** (KMS) and **in‑flight TLS**.<br>• Enable **DynamoDB server‑side encryption** (default) and **PITR**.<br>• Use **AWS KMS** with key policies that restrict decryption to specific IAM roles. | <https://docs.aws.amazon.com/efs/latest/ug/encryption.html> |
| **Resilience** | • Deploy **ALB/NLB** with **cross‑zone load balancing** and **health checks**.<br>• Use **Cluster Autoscaler** with **max‑node‑count** and **budget alerts**.<br>• Configure **PodDisruptionBudgets** for critical workloads. | <https://docs.aws.amazon.com/eks/latest/userguide/autoscaling.html> |
| **Compliance & Auditing** | • Enable **AWS Config** rules for EKS, VPC, IAM, and WAF.<br>• Periodically run **AWS Security Hub** standards (CIS‑EKS, PCI‑DSS). | <https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/what-is-config.html> |

